\subsection{Numerical results}

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\resizebox{0.6\linewidth}{!}{\input{FirstEx/OrderTau.tikz} }  
\caption{errors for $\tau$}
\label{fig:Orders2D}   
\end{figure}

In order to verify the order of convergence in case of killed diffusion \cite{Gobet2001}, let us perform a numerical experiment. We consider a two dimensional domain $D$ defined as
\begin{equation}\label{eq:domain}
	D = [-1,1]\times[-1,1], \quad D \subset \mathbb{R}^2.
\end{equation}
We consider the equation \eqref{eq:reference_equation} with the following parameters 
\begin{equation}\label{eq:parameters}
	T = 30,\: \sigma = 0.1,\: \mu = \begin{pmatrix} -0.9 \\ -0.9 \end{pmatrix}, \: X_0 = \begin{pmatrix} 0.5 \\ 0.5 \end{pmatrix}, \: A = \begin{pmatrix} 0.01 & 0 \\ 0 & 0.03 \end{pmatrix}
\end{equation}t
We perform a Montecarlo simulation over $M=10000$ trajectories, with timesteps $h_l = T/(2^l), l=1,\dots,6$, computing the parameters $\tau_h^d$ for the DEM \eqref{eq:DEM} and $\tau_h^c$ for the continuous Euler-Maruyama \eqref{eq:CEM}. We estimate the parameters $\tau$ with a Montecarlo simulation with the same number of trajectories of the exact solution \eqref{eq:exact_solution} using a timestep $h_{ex}$ much smaller than the smallest timestep used for the numerical solution. The convergence of our implementation of the numerical schemes is represented in Figure \ref{fig:Orders2D}. An example of typical trajectories for two timesteps is shown in Figure \ref{fig:Traj2D}.

\begin{figure}
\centering
\resizebox{0.6\linewidth}{!}{\input{FirstEx/Trajectories.tikz} }  
\label{Traj2D}
\caption{Two trajectories with different timesteps: with the smallest timestep an exit is detected.}
\end{figure}
